3/*++
4/* NAME
5/* record 3
6/* SUMMARY
7/* simple typed record I/O
8/* SYNOPSIS
9/* #include <record.h>
10/*
11/* int rec_get(stream, buf, maxsize)
12/* VSTREAM *stream;
13/* VSTRING *buf;
14/* ssize_t maxsize;
15/*
16/* int rec_get_raw(stream, buf, maxsize, flags)
17/* VSTREAM *stream;
18/* VSTRING *buf;
19/* ssize_t maxsize;
20/* int flags;
21/*
22/* int rec_put(stream, type, data, len)
23/* VSTREAM *stream;
24/* int type;
25/* const char *data;
26/* ssize_t len;
27/* AUXILIARY FUNCTIONS
28/* int rec_put_type(stream, type, offset)
29/* VSTREAM *stream;
30/* int type;
31/* long offset;
32/*
33/* int rec_fprintf(stream, type, format, ...)
34/* VSTREAM *stream;
35/* int type;
36/* const char *format;
37/*
38/* int rec_fputs(stream, type, str)
39/* VSTREAM *stream;
40/* int type;
41/* const char *str;
42/*
43/* int REC_PUT_BUF(stream, type, buf)
44/* VSTREAM *stream;
45/* int type;
46/* VSTRING *buf;
47/*
48/* int rec_vfprintf(stream, type, format, ap)
49/* VSTREAM *stream;
50/* int type;
51/* const char *format;
52/* va_list ap;
53/*
54/* int rec_goto(stream, where)
55/* VSTREAM *stream;
56/* const char *where;
57/*
58/* int rec_pad(stream, type, len)
59/* VSTREAM *stream;
60/* int type;
61/* ssize_t len;
62/*
63/* REC_SPACE_NEED(buflen, reclen)
64/* ssize_t buflen;
65/* ssize_t reclen;
66/*
67/* REC_GET_HIDDEN_TYPE(type)
68/* int type;
69/* DESCRIPTION
70/* This module reads and writes typed variable-length records.
71/* Each record contains a 1-byte type code (0..255), a length
72/* (1 or more bytes) and as much data as the length specifies.
73/*
74/* rec_get_raw() retrieves a record from the named record stream
75/* and returns the record type. The \fImaxsize\fR argument is
76/* zero, or specifies a maximal acceptable record length.
77/* The result is REC_TYPE_EOF when the end of the file was reached,
78/* and REC_TYPE_ERROR in case of a bad record. The result buffer is
79/* null-terminated for convenience. Records may contain embedded
80/* null characters. The \fIflags\fR argument specifies zero or
81/* more of the following:
82/* .IP REC_FLAG_FOLLOW_PTR
83/* Follow PTR records, instead of exposing them to the application.
84/* .IP REC_FLAG_SKIP_DTXT
85/* Skip "deleted text" records, instead of exposing them to
86/* the application.
87/* .IP REC_FLAG_SEEK_END
88/* Seek to the end-of-file upon reading a REC_TYPE_END record.
89/* .PP
90/* Specify REC_FLAG_NONE to request no special processing,
91/* and REC_FLAG_DEFAULT for normal use.
92/*
93/* rec_get() is a wrapper around rec_get_raw() that always
94/* enables the REC_FLAG_FOLLOW_PTR, REC_FLAG_SKIP_DTXT
95/* and REC_FLAG_SEEK_END features.
96/*
97/* REC_GET_HIDDEN_TYPE() is an unsafe macro that returns
98/* non-zero when the specified record type is "not exposed"
99/* by rec_get().
100/*
101/* rec_put() stores the specified record and returns the record
102/* type, or REC_TYPE_ERROR in case of problems.
103/*
104/* rec_put_type() updates the type field of the record at the
105/* specified file offset. The result is the new record type,
106/* or REC_TYPE_ERROR in case of trouble.
107/*
108/* rec_fprintf() and rec_vfprintf() format their arguments and
109/* write the result to the named stream. The result is the same
110/* as with rec_put().
111/*
112/* rec_fputs() writes a record with as contents a copy of the
113/* specified string. The result is the same as with rec_put().
114/*
115/* REC_PUT_BUF() is a wrapper for rec_put() that makes it
116/* easier to handle VSTRING buffers. It is an unsafe macro
117/* that evaluates some arguments more than once.
118/*
119/* rec_goto() takes the argument of a pointer record and moves
120/* the file pointer to the specified location. A zero position
121/* means do nothing. The result is REC_TYPE_ERROR in case of
122/* failure.
123/*
124/* rec_pad() writes a record that occupies the larger of (the
125/* specified amount) or (an implementation-defined minimum).
126/*
127/* REC_SPACE_NEED(buflen, reclen) converts the specified buffer
128/* length into a record length. This macro modifies its second
129/* argument.
130/* DIAGNOSTICS
131/* Panics: interface violations. Fatal errors: insufficient memory.
132/* Warnings: corrupted file.
133/* LICENSE
134/* .ad
135/* .fi
136/* The Secure Mailer license must be distributed with this software.
137/* AUTHOR(S)
138/* Wietse Venema
139/* IBM T.J. Watson Research
140/* P.O. Box 704
141/* Yorktown Heights, NY 10598, USA
142/*--*/
143

147#include <stdlib.h> /* 44BSD stdarg.h uses abort() */
148#include <stdarg.h>
149#include <unistd.h>
150#include <string.h>
151
152#ifndef NBBY
153#define NBBY 8 /* XXX should be in sys_defs.h */
154#endif
155
156/* Utility library. */

158#include <msg.h>
159#include <mymalloc.h>
160#include <vstream.h>
161#include <vstring.h>
162#include <stringops.h>
163
164/* Global library. */
165

167#include <rec_type.h>
168#include <record.h>

170/* rec_put_type - update record type field */
171
172int rec_put_type(VSTREAM *stream, int type, off_t offset)
173{
174 if (type < 0 || type > 255)
175 msg_panic("rec_put_type: bad record type %d", type);
176
177 if (msg_verbose > 2)
178 msg_info("rec_put_type: %d at %ld", type, (long) offset);
179
180 if (vstream_fseek(stream, offset, SEEK_SET) < 0
181 || VSTREAM_PUTC(type, stream) != type) {
182 msg_warn("%s: seek or write error", VSTREAM_PATH(stream));
183 return (REC_TYPE_ERROR);
184 } else {
185 return (type);
186 }
187}
188
189/* rec_put - store typed record */
190
191int rec_put(VSTREAM *stream, int type, const char *data, ssize_t len)
192{
193 ssize_t len_rest;
194 int len_byte;
195
196 if (type < 0 || type > 255)
197 msg_panic("rec_put: bad record type %d", type);
198
199 if (msg_verbose > 2)
200 msg_info("rec_put: type %c len %ld data %.10s",
201 type, (long) len, data);
202
203 /*
204 * Write the record type, one byte.
205 */
206 if (VSTREAM_PUTC(type, stream) == VSTREAM_EOF)
207 return (REC_TYPE_ERROR);
208
209 /*
210 * Write the record data length in 7-bit portions, using the 8th bit to
211 * indicate that there is more. Use as many length bytes as needed.
212 */
213 len_rest = len;
214 do {
215 len_byte = len_rest & 0177;
216 if (len_rest >>= 7U)
217 len_byte |= 0200;
218 if (VSTREAM_PUTC(len_byte, stream) == VSTREAM_EOF) {
219 return (REC_TYPE_ERROR);
220 }
221 } while (len_rest != 0);
222
223 /*
224 * Write the record data portion. Use as many length bytes as needed.
225 */
226 if (len && vstream_fwrite(stream, data, len) != len)
227 return (REC_TYPE_ERROR);
228 return (type);
229}
230
231/* rec_get_raw - retrieve typed record */
232
233int rec_get_raw(VSTREAM *stream, VSTRING *buf, ssize_t maxsize, int flags)
234{
235 const char *myname = "rec_get";
236 int type;
237 ssize_t len;
238 int len_byte;
239 unsigned shift;
240
241 /*
242 * Sanity check.
243 */
244 if (maxsize < 0)
245 msg_panic("%s: bad record size limit: %ld", myname, (long) maxsize);
246
247 for (;;) {
248
249 /*
250 * Extract the record type.
251 */
252 if ((type = VSTREAM_GETC(stream)) == VSTREAM_EOF)
253 return (REC_TYPE_EOF);
254
255 /*
256 * Find out the record data length. Return an error result when the
257 * record data length is malformed or when it exceeds the acceptable
258 * limit.
259 */
260 for (len = 0, shift = 0; /* void */ ; shift += 7) {
261 if (shift >= (int) (NBBY * sizeof(int))) {
262 msg_warn("%s: too many length bits, record type %d",
263 VSTREAM_PATH(stream), type);
264 return (REC_TYPE_ERROR);
265 }
266 if ((len_byte = VSTREAM_GETC(stream)) == VSTREAM_EOF) {
267 msg_warn("%s: unexpected EOF reading length, record type %d",
268 VSTREAM_PATH(stream), type);
269 return (REC_TYPE_ERROR);
270 }
271 len |= (len_byte & 0177) << shift;
272 if ((len_byte & 0200) == 0)
273 break;
274 }
275 if (len < 0 || (maxsize > 0 && len > maxsize)) {
276 msg_warn("%s: illegal length %ld, record type %d",
277 VSTREAM_PATH(stream), (long) len, type);
278 while (len-- > 0 && VSTREAM_GETC(stream) != VSTREAM_EOF)
279 /* void */ ;
280 return (REC_TYPE_ERROR);
281 }
282
283 /*
284 * Reserve buffer space for the result, and read the record data into
285 * the buffer.
286 */
287 VSTRING_RESET(buf);
288 VSTRING_SPACE(buf, len);
289 if (vstream_fread(stream, vstring_str(buf), len) != len) {
290 msg_warn("%s: unexpected EOF in data, record type %d length %ld",
291 VSTREAM_PATH(stream), type, (long) len);
292 return (REC_TYPE_ERROR);
293 }
294 VSTRING_AT_OFFSET(buf, len);
295 VSTRING_TERMINATE(buf);
296 if (msg_verbose > 2)
297 msg_info("%s: type %c len %ld data %.10s", myname,
298 type, (long) len, vstring_str(buf));
299
300 /*
301 * Transparency options.
302 */
303 if (flags == 0)
304 break;
305 if (type == REC_TYPE_PTR && (flags & REC_FLAG_FOLLOW_PTR) != 0
306 && (type = rec_goto(stream, vstring_str(buf))) != REC_TYPE_ERROR)
307 continue;
308 if (type == REC_TYPE_DTXT && (flags & REC_FLAG_SKIP_DTXT) != 0)
309 continue;
310 if (type == REC_TYPE_END && (flags & REC_FLAG_SEEK_END) != 0
311 && vstream_fseek(stream, (off_t) 0, SEEK_END) < 0) {
312 msg_warn("%s: seek error after reading END record: %m",
313 VSTREAM_PATH(stream));
314 return (REC_TYPE_ERROR);
315 }
316 break;
317 }
318 return (type);
319}

321/* rec_goto - follow PTR record */
322
323int rec_goto(VSTREAM *stream, const char *buf)
324{
325 off_t offset;
326 static const char *saved_path;
327 static off_t saved_offset;
328 static int reverse_count;
329
330 /*
331 * Crude workaround for queue file loops. VSTREAMs currently have no
332 * option to attach application-specific data, so we use global state and
333 * simple logic to detect if an application switches streams. We trigger
334 * on reverse jumps only. There's one reverse jump for every inserted
335 * header, but only one reverse jump for all appended recipients. No-one
336 * is likely to insert 10000 message headers, but someone might append
337 * 10000 recipients.
338 */
339#define STREQ(x,y) ((x) == (y) && strcmp((x), (y)) == 0)
340#define REVERSE_JUMP_LIMIT 10000
341
342 if (!STREQ(saved_path, VSTREAM_PATH(stream))) {
343 saved_path = VSTREAM_PATH(stream);
344 reverse_count = 0;
345 saved_offset = 0;
346 }
347 while (ISSPACE(*buf))
348 buf++;
349 if ((offset = off_cvt_string(buf)) < 0) {
350 msg_warn("%s: malformed pointer record value: %s",
351 VSTREAM_PATH(stream), buf);
352 return (REC_TYPE_ERROR);
353 } else if (offset == 0) {
354 /* Dummy record. */
355 return (0);
356 } else if (offset <= saved_offset && ++reverse_count > REVERSE_JUMP_LIMIT) {
357 msg_warn("%s: too many reverse jump records", VSTREAM_PATH(stream));
358 return (REC_TYPE_ERROR);
359 } else if (vstream_fseek(stream, offset, SEEK_SET) < 0) {
360 msg_warn("%s: seek error after pointer record: %m",
361 VSTREAM_PATH(stream));
362 return (REC_TYPE_ERROR);
363 } else {
364 saved_offset = offset;
365 return (0);
366 }
367}

369/* rec_vfprintf - write formatted string to record */
370
371int rec_vfprintf(VSTREAM *stream, int type, const char *format, va_list ap)
372{
373 static VSTRING *vp;
374
375 if (vp == 0)
376 vp = vstring_alloc(100);
377
378 /*
379 * Writing a formatted string involves an extra copy, because we must
380 * know the record length before we can write it.
381 */
382 vstring_vsprintf(vp, format, ap);
383 return (REC_PUT_BUF(stream, type, vp));
384}
385
386/* rec_fprintf - write formatted string to record */
387
388int rec_fprintf(VSTREAM *stream, int type, const char *format,...)
389{
390 int result;
391 va_list ap;
392
393 va_start(ap, format);
394 result = rec_vfprintf(stream, type, format, ap);
395 va_end(ap);
396 return (result);
397}
398
399/* rec_fputs - write string to record */
400
401int rec_fputs(VSTREAM *stream, int type, const char *str)
402{
403 return (rec_put(stream, type, str, str ? strlen(str) : 0));
404}
405
406/* rec_pad - write padding record */
407
408int rec_pad(VSTREAM *stream, int type, ssize_t len)
409{
410 int width = len - 2; /* type + length */
411
412 return (rec_fprintf(stream, type, "%*s",
413 width < 1 ? 1 : width, "0"));
414}
